design:
FILES TO MODIFY:
- src/components/App.tsx
  - Tab union: type Tab = 'plan' | 'map' | 'journey'
  - Add a third tab button to the existing tab-nav, following the exact same role/className/aria-selected pattern:
    <button
      role="tab"
      aria-selected={tab === 'journey'}
      className={`tab-btn${tab === 'journey' ? ' active' : ''}`}
      onClick={() => setTab('journey')}
    >
      Journey
    </button>
  - In the render switch, add a third branch:
    {tab === 'plan' ? <PlanView ... />
     : tab === 'map' ? <MapView ... />
     : <JourneyView stages={data.stages} markers={data.markers} route={data.route} routeSplitIndex={data.routeSplitIndex} />}
  - Import JourneyView at the top.

- src/components/App.test.tsx
  - Add a test: clicking the "Journey" tab shows the journey view. Assert on a class or text that's unique to JourneyView (e.g. .journey-stage-label or the label format "Stage 1 — ..."). Keep this test small — it's a smoke check that the third tab is wired, not a re-test of JourneyView internals.

- src/index.css — append a small block of journey-* rules. Reuse existing CSS variables. Suggested rules (adjust to match the established formatting in this file):
  .journey-view { display: flex; flex-direction: column; height: 100%; }
  .journey-map { height: 60vh; width: 100%; }
  @media (max-width: 640px) { .journey-map { height: 55vh; } }
  .journey-stage-label { padding: 0.5rem 1rem 0; font-size: 0.85rem; letter-spacing: 0.05em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent, #e2b96f); opacity: 0.85; }
  .journey-slider-row { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; padding: 0.5rem 1rem; }
  .journey-slider-range { flex: 1; }
  .journey-slider-prev, .journey-slider-next {
    background: transparent; border: 1px solid var(--border, #333); color: inherit;
    width: 2rem; height: 2rem; border-radius: 50%; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1.1rem;
  }
  .journey-slider-prev:disabled, .journey-slider-next:disabled { opacity: 0.4; cursor: default; }
  .journey-day-label { padding: 0 1rem 0.5rem; font-size: 0.85rem; opacity: 0.75; text-align: center; }
  IMPORTANT: read src/index.css before adding — match existing variable names (the actual CSS variable name might be --accent-gold or similar). Don't introduce new variables; use whatever the file already defines for accent/border/text.

VERIFY BY (manual, after running npm run dev):
1. Three tabs visible in the header: Plan, Map, Journey.
2. Clicking Journey shows the new view. Map renders at the top, day card middle, slider at the bottom with prev/next chevrons.
3. Dragging the slider visibly pans/zooms the map and updates the day card and stage label.
4. Prev/next chevrons step one entry; clamp at the ends (visually disabled at index 0 and final).
5. Existing Plan and Map tabs unchanged.
6. Layout looks coherent at narrow (~390px) and wide (~1200px) viewport widths.

VERIFY BY (automated):
1. npm run test:run — green (existing tests + the new App.test.tsx assertion).
2. npm run build — typecheck clean, build succeeds.

DO NOT:
- Re-style existing tab buttons or the header.
- Change Plan or Map tab behavior.
- Introduce new color tokens — reuse existing variables.
- Add scroll containers or sticky positioning unless layout actually requires it; the spec uses a simple vertical stack.

DEPENDS ON: JourneyView task.
